In the light of recent research findings the inappropriateness of many commonly accepted concepts in psychosomatic medicine is discussed. They do not stand up to empirical scrutiny. This applies both to sepcifity models and to duality of body and mind or of illness and health. The monocausal-psychogenetic view was replaced through a complex interplay of hierarchie somato-psychic circles which are to be integrated into a biosemiotic model. In terms of the self-object-body system a greater significance is attached to affects in the communication and acting receives an important interactive function. The effects of the altered theroretical positions on new therapy approaches are discussed.  
